@Node History "Program History"

 History
 =======

 1.0  - First release

 1.01 - The string 'Packing \"%s\" for %lu:%lu/%lu.%lu with %s' was logged
        with the prefix TICKERR ("!") instead of TICKINFO ("=").

      - In some places in CrashTickPrefs, all visible changes were lost 
        when you selected something in a requester that popped up. This 
        happened in Areas/Raid, Nodes/Raid and Announce.

      - Fixed a small mistake in the Swedish catalog: The description string
        for the Add requester in CrashTickPrefs/Areas was wrong...

      - A mistake in the manual: The command needed to pass an RFC-message
        to the Raid part of CrashTick when using CrashMail was wrong. The
        correct command string is:

        MAIL:CrashTick RAID %r

        My apologies to everybody who has had trouble because of this...

      - CrashTickPrefs forgot to tell you that the settings had been changed
        if you only changed the access a node had to an area...

 1.1  - It is now possible to use wildcards when attaching to areas or
        detaching from areas in Raid. A downlink can always use "*" as a
        wildcard even if you haven't activated it as a wildcard on your
        Amiga, since CrashMail replaces all occurences of "*" with "#?"
        before the wildcard string is passed to the functions in the
        operating system.

        This change has also led to that CrashTick no longer gives you
        different log messages that tells you if a downlink tried to
        attach to an area to which he had no access or to an area which
        doesn't exist, these two cases now produce the same log message.

      - You can now configure a command that should be executed everytime
        CrashTick imports a file that came with a .tic file that contained
        a "Magic"-line with information about a recommended magic name
        for file requests. If there are several lines with magic names,
        the configured command is executed several times. This could be
        used to update the configuration of your file request handler.

      - It is now possible to configure a "Userdata/Area number" string for
        each area in your configuration. CrashTick doesn't use this string
        at all, but you can pass it to external commands using a %-code. The
        reason for this is that you can't add a file to a file area without
        an area number in many BBS programs. This new function should make
        it a lot easier to use CrashTick together with such programs. You
        can use this string for other purposes too, if you like to...

      - CrashTick now writes the file name and the destination node in the
        file comment of the .tic files it creates. This makes it easier to
        see what file a .tic file belongs to.

      - It is now possible to configure CrashTick to announce files to
        normal textfiles instead of .PKT files. If the file already exists,
        CrashTick will append to it, so you could for example use this to
        make a list of all files that you have received.

      - CrashTickPrefs now lets you import descriptions for your areas from
        a file in FILEBONE.NA format or from a textfile that just contains
        the descriptions in the form "<areaname> <description>".

      - A new "Change areas" function has been added to CrashTickPrefs. This
        powerful new function lets you change configuration items of several
        areas without changing all areas separately.

      - A new ARexx script called RaidUMS.rexx has been included. If you are
        using a UMS messagebase, you can use this script to generate messages
        in RFC format which the Raid in CrashTick can read.

      - In the previous versions of CrashTick, there was no way that you
        could have just a '%'-character in an external command because of
        the %-codes. Now you can use "%%" if you just want a '%'-character.

 1.2  CrashTick 1.11 was never really released, but was only available as a
      beta version on my homepage. Only some of these changes will be new to
      those who downloaded that beta version.

      - CrashTick and CrashTickPrefs now allocate a larger stack and will
        now work with newer versions of gtlayout.library without any problems.

      - If you tried to do a "CrashTick maint" and your Filebase directory
        didn't exist, CrashTick would give you a wrong error message and tell
        you that the Inbound directory didn't exist. Fixed in this version.

      - The Group selection window in CrashTickPrefs didn't have the correct
        window title. Fixed.

      - When "Max wait before pickup" was changed in CrashTickPrefs/General,
        the new value would be copied to the maximum buffer values for the
        logfile too. This has now been fixed.

      - When a file or a directory was selected with the file requester in
        CrashTickPrefs/Areas or CrashTickPrefs/Announce, CrashTickPrefs
        would forget to tell you that the config had been changed.

      - Now you can set a group to "Incoming only" for a node.

      - A new option called "No .tic files" has been added. If this switch
        is set for a node, the node will receive the files without the
        accompanying tick files.

      - It is now possible to specify a "Magic" name when hatching a file.

      - RaidHelp.doc has been updated, mostly layout changes.

      - A new tool called CrashTickHatch has now been included. This tool
        lets you hatch files comfortably with a GUI.

      These changes are new since the CrashTick 1.11 beta:

      - Five new ARexx commands and command-line arguments have been
        introduced: SENDQUERY, SENDLIST, SENDUNLINKED, SENDINFO and
        SENDHELP. The NOTIFY ARexx command and command-line argument
        still works, but is just an alias for SENDQUERY.

      - The %UNLINKED command used to send a list of all areas the node was
        not connected to, this unfortunately also included those areas the
        node didn't have access to. Now %UNLINKED only includes the areas
        that the node actually ahs access to.

      - When CrashTick passes on commands to another copy of CrashTick, it
        now prints the sent ARexx command on the screen and displays the
        result when the command has been executed. Users of TrapDispatcher
        will recognize it from that program.

      - You can now configure a maximum number of lines in the Raid
        responses created by CrashTick. This was introduced since many
        programs can't handle too long netmails. You can set this in
        CrashTickPrefs/General.

      - Because  of a bug, CrashTick didn't sort the files before creating
        an announcement. Fixed.

@EndNode

